Now, in the doctrine of Transubstantiation, it is affirmed that the bread ceases to exist. This (though some Doctors of great note, Aquinas amongst others, explain it in a different manner> certainly seems to point to annihilation, as was very probably admitted by Wyclif⁷s Nominalistic opponentS. At any rate, the assertion that the whole substance of the bread ceases to exist at a given instant — both as to its substantial qualities and the underlying substratum of those qualities — could, in Wyclif's system, be understood only as the annihilation of the atoms of which it consists. This had to be denied. The bread, it was affirmed, ceased to exist as bread,· in its place there remained a body that Wyclif (no doubt out of respect for the dogma which he still seemed to admit) called a corpus mathematicmn.
